{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473947"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11561"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11561"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.01,0.09,0.71,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4190"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-02-08T20:16:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T17:45:12+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-06-29T19:54:29+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-23 07:46:58"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11561"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92089"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"4068"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41100"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92089"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109686"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with primary amenorrhoea. She has not yet reached menarche. Her mother and sister experienced menarche when they were 13 years old. She has no significant medical history and otherwise normal development. She does not take any regular medications and is not sexually active.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 39 kg/m2. She has Tanner stage V development. There is acne across her face and back, dark hair on her upper lip and chin, and normal breast development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFSH: 7 mIU/mL (5-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELH: 21 mIU/mL (5-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal Testosterone: 101 ng/dL (6.0-86)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFree Testosterone: 4.0 pg/mL (0.7-3.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDHEA-S: 450 \u00b5g/dL (35-430)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProlactin: 16 ng/mL (\u0026lt;25)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOestrogen: 49 pg/mL (25-75)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProgesterone: 10 ng/mL (\u0026gt;14 indicative of ovulation)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E17-hydroxyprogesterone: 1.5 ng/mL (\u0026lt;2.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH: 1.2 \u00b5IU/mL (0.4-3.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EbHCG (urine): negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransabdominal pelvic ultrasound shows a normal sized anteverted uterus with normal endometrium and myometrium. Two ovaries of normal size are seen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her amenorrhoea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Late-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia","Hyperprolactinaemia","Primary ovarian insufficiency","Polycystic ovarian syndrome","Mullerian agenesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of this woman\u0027s primary amenorrhoea is \u003Cstrong\u003Epolycystic ovarian syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (PCOS). This diagnosis is supported by the presence of hirsutism (dark hair on upper lip and chin), acne, obesity (BMI 39 kg/m2), and abnormal biochemical markers, particularly the raised free testosterone. The elevated LH and normal FSH also suggest suppressed ovulation, which is characteristic of PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Rotterdam Criteria are used to diagnose PCOS, requiring at least two of the following: oligo/anovulation, polycystic ovaries on ultrasound, or hyperandrogenism (biochemical or clinical). In this case, the patient has oligo/anovulation (primary amenorrhoea) and hyperandrogenism (both clinical with hirsutism and acne, and biochemical with elevated free testosterone) with a normal ultrasound findings. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELate-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E (CAH) can present similarly to PCOS with hyperandrogenism. However, late-onset CAH typically results in elevated 17-hydroxyprogesterone levels, which are normal in this patient (1.5 ng/mL).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperprolactinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes decreased LH, FSH, and oestrogen levels, with raised prolactin. In this case, prolactin is normal (16 ng/mL), and LH is elevated, making hyperprolactinaemia unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary ovarian insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by increased LH and FSH levels with decreased oestrogen, similar to menopause. This patient\u0027s FSH is normal, and features of hyperandrogenism (hirsutism, acne) are uncommon in primary ovarian insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of a normal uterus on ultrasound rules out \u003Cstrong\u003EMullerian agenesis\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterized by the absence of a uterus, vagina, or both due to failed development of the Mullerian duct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Polycystic ovarian syndrome is a metabolic disorder that is diagnosed by the presence of two or more of: oligo/amenorrhoea, hyperandrogenism, or polycystic ovaries on ultrasound.","The Rotterdam Criteria is used to diagnose PCOS, requiring at least two of: oligo/anovulation, polycystic ovaries on ultrasound, or hyperandrogenism (biochemical or clinical).","Hyperandrogenism in PCOS can manifest as hirsutism, acne, and elevated free testosterone levels."],"references":["Klein DA, Poth MA. Amenorrhea: an approach to diagnosis and management. Am Fam Physician. 2013;87(11):781-8","Witchel SF, Burghard AC, Tao RH, Oberfield SE. The diagnosis and treatment of PCOS in adolescents: an update. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2019 Aug;31(4):562-569. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0000000000000778. PMID: 31299022.","Hoeger KM, Dokras A, Piltonen T. Update on PCOS: Consequences, Challenges, and Guiding Treatment. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2021 Mar 8;106(3):e1071-e1083. doi: 10.1210/clinem/dgaa839. PMID: 33211867.","Sterling E. Hormone Levels and PCOS. Contemporary OB/GYN. 2011 [cited 15 May 2022]. Available from: https://www.contemporaryobgyn.net/view/hormone-levels-and-pcos","Jha S, Turcu AF. Nonclassic Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia: What Do Endocrinologists Need to Know? Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2021 Mar;50(1):151-165. doi: 10.1016/j.ecl.2020.10.008."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92089"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11561"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92089"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-24T17:44:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T17:45:58+09:30","number":13,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-07-24T17:45:13+09:30","plagiarismScore":5.3,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4190-13.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T124619Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=c2bdeaf18dfa92ab7499752261aa38975cbf68f9d44eed6bb756588adc509d86"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4190"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109686"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":n